function solve(nums) {
    const n = nums.length;
    const sortedNums = [...nums].sort((a, b) => a - b);

    /**
     * Checks if an array (or sub-array) can be sorted by cyclic shifts.
     * An array can be sorted by cyclic shifts if and only if it is a cyclic permutation
     * of the sorted version of itself.
     * Since we are dealing with contiguous segments of the target sorted array,
     * if the elements within a segment match the expected elements from the sorted array,
     * the only requirement is that the set of elements is correct.
     * However, the problem states "independent cyclic shift".
     * A sequence can be sorted by cyclic shift if and only if it is a cyclic shift of the sorted sequence.
     * For a segment of length k, let S be the sorted version of the segment. The original segment
     * must be a cyclic permutation of S.
     * A simpler condition for an array A of length k to be transformable into its sorted version S
     * via cyclic shifts is that A must be a cyclic shift of S.
     * This means A must be a rotation of S.
     * Example: S = [1, 2, 3]. Rotations: [1, 2, 3], [2, 3, 1], [3, 1, 2].
     *
     * @param {number[]} segment The segment of length k.
     * @param {number[]} targetSorted The full sorted array.
     * @param {number} start The starting index of the segment in the original array (and sorted array).
     * @param {number} k The length of the segment.
     * @returns {boolean} True if the segment can be cyclically shifted to match the sorted order.
